13- Wk20 Liver, bile and biliary tree 

Saturday, September 23, 2017 

3:40 PM 

Consider the orientation of the liver, and examine the proximity of the liver to other abdominal organs 

 

 

A vertical ligament exists on the backside of the liver, called the ligamentum venosum. It connects the liver and portal vein to the lesser omentum of the peritoneum. The liver is intra-peritoneal, and is covered by the peritoneum except the bare area which is in contact with the diaphragm: 

 

The bare area of the liver is clinically important as it represents a site where infection can spread from the abdominal cavity to the thoracic cavity.  

 

Blood supply 

The celiac trunk splits into the common hepatic artery, which splits into the gastroduodenal artery and the hepatic artery proper. This then splits into its right and left branch. The portal vein carries blood from the superior mesenteric vein and splenic vein (with blood from branching inferior mesenteric vein). The right and left hepatic veins then drain hepatic blood directly into the IVC.  

 

Porta hepatis 

 

 

 

Gallbladder 

 

 

The cystic artery arises from the right hepatic artery proper, from the common hepatic artery from the celiac trunk.  

 

Pancreas 

The pancreas is made of an uncinate process, a head, a neck, a body and a tail. It is retroperitoneal and developed from two ducts: rotation and fusion gives adult pattern.  

 

Blood supply 

The splenic artery branches off to give arteries supplying the body and tail of the pancreas. The common hepatic artery branches off to give the gastroduodenal artery, which branches to give the posterior superior pancreaticoduodenal artery supplying the uncinate process. The superior mesenteric artery also branches off to give the anterior branch of inferior pancreaticoduodenal artery.  

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

 

Spleen 

The spleen is intraperitoneal, developing within the dorsal mesentery. It is connected to the stomach by the gastrosplenic ligament, and to the kidney by the splenorenal ligament. Both are continuous with the greater omentum.  

 

Note: the greater omentum also includes the gastrophrenic and gastrocolic ligaments.
